I'm here today to learn more
about Adventure Scientists

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:04.620
and how to collect
data on butterflies

00:01:04.620 --> 00:01:08.160
and flowering plants for
Adventure Scientists projects

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:09.205
that are going on.

00:01:09.205 --> 00:01:10.830
MICHELLE TOSHACK:
Adventures Scientists

00:01:10.830 --> 00:01:14.670
is a nonprofit based
out of Bozeman, Montana.

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:17.110
We do the volunteer management.

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:19.170
And then we partner
with researchers

00:01:19.170 --> 00:01:23.490
who have specific
conservation concerns where

00:01:23.490 --> 00:01:25.900
data is a limiting factor.

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:29.160
And so we have this
network of volunteers,

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:32.280
not only over the US
but through the world.

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:34.497
Some of our projects
are global projects.

00:01:34.497 --> 00:01:36.330
KATY PRUDIC: So the
proboscis is out, right?

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:39.990
So he's probing with his
proboscis, which is his straw.

00:01:39.990 --> 00:01:44.850
Butterflies are great indicators
of how an ecosystem is doing.

00:01:44.850 --> 00:01:49.290
I think it signifies whether
this habitat is working,

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:53.910
whether it's able to
support a variety of life,

00:01:53.910 --> 00:01:57.520
whether you'll have a lot of
birds there, a lot of mammals.

00:01:57.520 --> 00:02:00.180
A lot of interactions
are happening.

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:05.530
So a diverse place is often
a very productive place.

